<body>
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Pony Flowers Admin Panel & Cloud Integration Walkthrough</h1>
    <p>This document outlines the features and verification steps for the new Pony Flowers administrative control panel, upgraded checkout flow, and cloud data synchronization setup.</p>
    
    <div class="highlight-box">
      <strong>Note:</strong> All changes have been deployed client-side. The admin dashboard defaults to a local Sandbox environment (storing data in your browser's local storage) so you can preview and test it immediately without configuration. Instructions are provided below to connect your Firebase cloud database.
    </div>

    <h2>1. Overview of Key Features Built</h2>
    
    <h3>Upgraded Storefront Checkout</h3>
    <p>We replaced the placeholder checkout process with a full customer details form. Clicking "Proceed to Checkout" in the shopping cart now opens a dialog collecting:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Full Name:</strong> The customer's identity.</li>
      <li><strong>Phone Number:</strong> For delivery notifications.</li>
      <li><strong>Delivery Address:</strong> Detailed location for drop-off.</li>
      <li><strong>Delivery Date:</strong> Date selector (validated to block past dates).</li>
      <li><strong>Gift Message:</strong> Optional handwritten card content.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Submitting the form generates a unique reference code (e.g., #PONY-48291), saves the order, and clears the cart.</p>

    <h3>Dynamic Storefront Catalog</h3>
    <p>The shop catalog is now dynamic. On load, the store initializes the <strong>PONY_DB</strong> script, fetching products. If the database is empty (such as during first load), the script automatically extracts the default 20 products from the HTML markup and seeds the catalog. Event delegation is used so that adding or removing products dynamically immediately updates the shopping listeners without reload.</p>

    <h3>Admin Panel Dashboard (admin.html)</h3>
    <p>A styled administrative control board tailored to Pony's premium branding:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Dashboard Statistics:</strong> Shows cumulative revenue, active catalog counts, total orders, and pending delivery counts.</li>
      <li><strong>Order Invoice Viewer:</strong> View full invoices, contact details, date, items ordered, and gift card messages. Change order status instantly using the dropdown (Pending, Preparing, Out for Delivery, Delivered, Cancelled).</li>
      <li><strong>Product Manager:</strong> Add new flowers (category selection, pricing, specs, descriptions, custom image URLs), edit existing details, and delete cards from the storefront.</li>
      <li><strong>Database Setup Wizard:</strong> Guides you through creating a free Google Firebase account and connecting it to save shop data globally.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2. Step-by-Step Verification Guide</h2>
    
    <h3>Step 1: Access the Dashboard</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Open your store website (<a href="index.html" class="btn-link">index.html</a>) in any web browser.</li>
      <li>Scroll down to the footer page bottom and click the <strong>Admin Dashboard</strong> link (or open <a href="admin.html" class="btn-link">admin.html</a> directly).</li>
      <li>Log in with the sandbox password: <span class="code-block" style="display:inline; padding: 2px 6px;">admin123</span></li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Step 2: Add a Custom Product</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Click on the <strong>Flowers Catalog</strong> tab in the sidebar menu.</li>
      <li>Select the <strong>Add New Flower Card</strong> button.</li>
      <li>Enter details for a new product, e.g.:
        <ul>
          <li>Name: "Admin Special Rose"</li>
          <li>Price: "45000"</li>
          <li>Category: "Roses"</li>
          <li>Variety: "Rosa hybrida · 15 stems"</li>
          <li>Badge: "🌟 Exclusive"</li>
          <li>Image: "images/rose1.png"</li>
          <li>Description: "A special bouquet created from the admin dashboard."</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Click <strong>Add Flower</strong> and check that it appears in your catalog catalog list.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Step 3: Test Storefront Checkout</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Go back to the storefront (<a href="index.html" class="btn-link">index.html</a>) and refresh the page.</li>
      <li>Find the new product under the Roses tab and click the <strong>+</strong> add button.</li>
      <li>Open the shopping cart drawer and click <strong>Proceed to Checkout</strong>.</li>
      <li>Fill out the form: Name: "Jane Smith", Phone: "+234 81 2345 6789", Address: "12 Orchid Way, Lagos", Date: select tomorrow's date. Click <strong>Place Order</strong>.</li>
      <li>Note the reference code shown on success.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Step 4: Update Order Status</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Navigate back to the Admin Dashboard (<a href="admin.html" class="btn-link">admin.html</a>).</li>
      <li>Check the <strong>Dashboard Overview</strong> and the <strong>Orders</strong> tab.</li>
      <li>Locate the new order from Jane Smith, click <strong>Inspect</strong>.</li>
      <li>Change the status dropdown to <strong>Preparing</strong> and then <strong>Out for Delivery</strong>.</li>
      <li>Close the invoice modal to see the status tag update in real-time.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>3. Cloud Synchronization Setup (Firebase)</h2>
    <p>To launch live on multiple devices, connect a cloud database in the <strong>Database Config</strong> tab:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Create a project on the <a href="https://console.firebase.google.com/" target="_blank">Google Firebase Console</a>.</li>
      <li>Enable <strong>Firestore Database</strong> and <strong>Authentication</strong> (Email/Password).</li>
      <li>Register a Web App in Project Settings, copy the configuration JSON block.</li>
      <li>Paste it into the <strong>Database Config</strong> setup field in your Admin Panel and click Connect.</li>
      <li>Your store will instantly transition from local sandbox to live cloud database synchronization!</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="footer">
      Pony Flowers Administration Console Guide • Generated on June 19, 2026
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
